The One-Line Pitch

"CodeCraft turns final-year engineering students into job-ready developers by simulating their first job before they ever apply for one."


Founder's Unfair Advantage to Build This
The problem is real, measurable (Severity 9), and the market is massive — India alone produces 15 lakh engineering graduates per year. Even capturing 1% of that at ₹1,200/month is a ₹180 Cr/year market from students alone, before touching the B2B side.
The insight that colleges won't be disrupted but can be partnered with is the key to distribution at scale without massive CAC.


Why Monaco Editor over building your own IDE — it's the exact same engine as VS Code. Students get a professional-grade editor from day one, and you ship it in one sprint instead of six.

Why Supabase over a custom backend — you get auth, database, file storage, and real-time subscriptions in one service. A two-person team shouldn't be managing servers in month one.

Why Judge0 for code execution — building a secure code sandbox is a genuine engineering rabbit hole. Judge0 solves container isolation, timeout enforcement, and multi-language support out of the box. Outsource it and stay focused on the product.

Why the content lead is the most underrated hire — the tickets are the product. A mediocre AI feedback engine on top of great, realistic tickets still works. A great AI engine on top of vague, unrealistic tickets fails every time. Hire someone who has actually worked in a dev team to write them.

The single most important thing to do in Month 5 — get your first 10 real placements. Even one student who lands a job because of CodeCraft gives you a story that sells every B2B conversation with companies and colleges for the next year. That outcome data is worth more than any feature you could build.
